sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J119126
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part is a Promoter-cDog-trpR (tryptophan repressor gene) that will feed back into the tryptophan promoter when tryptophan is in high enough concentration. It is designed to be used in conjunction with the tryptophan operon optimization experiments.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Caleb J. Carr
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The S05028 part was synthesized by the Davidson team, and the J119124 part was cloned out of the native genome of E. coli using primers.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The scar that would result, as it ends up just between the cDog and the gene to be translated.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J119028
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: BD24 bicistronic translational junction - Highest efficiency
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The BD24 bicistronic translational junction was engineered by Vivek Mutalik and The BIOFAB Team at biofab.org. It includes an RBS that allows translation of a leader polypeptide. The leader has a second RBS embedded in it. The stop codon for the leader polypeptide overlaps with the start codon for the gene of interest.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vivek Mutalik
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The bicistronic translational junction was designed by Team Leader Vivek Mutalik at BioFAB [http://www.biofab.org]. It is is intended to give reproducible and consistent expression for various genes of interest.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_J119124
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: trpR, tryptophan-repressor, represses the Promoter-tryp when tryp is high
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the tryptophan-Repressor, which represses the tryptophan-promoter (BBa_J119124), when tryptophan has reached a high enough concentration in the cell. Designed to be part of a selection module for optimization of the tryptophan operon, its intended function is to down-regulate or entirely shut off a gene promoted by the Ptrp, said gene having a negative effect on the cell in some way.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Caleb J. Carr
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Primers were used to "pull" this part from the E. coli genome.
